author: nads
text:
new gym and very well equipped. plenty of bench/squat racks and free weights that has a wide range from 1-2kg upwards to 50kg.

large functional and pin loaded machines as well.

the interesting thing about this gym is that it has a ping pong / table tennis area, so i guess if you wanna play can come here and play ??

but equipment overall is good, good selection between the other 2 AF's in the area of wheelock and 313

author: Jonny Jonny
text:
How is grunting and shouting for my last 2 reps considered rowdy behaviour? I have never been to an Anytime Fitness that has told me off for my "rowdy behaviour".
To be clear, I was not shouting between my sets or talking loudly; I was just pushing to get the last 2 reps in.
I was told off twice, first for slamming the weight and the cable pull. I admit I did slam it due to my overestimation of myself on the weight I could handle, which hastily prompted the staff to come over and tell me to relax a bit on slamming the weights.
The second time was at the dumbbell area, I was doing curls at my 6-8 rep, I was grunting and "shouting" in the staff's words. Which in turn prompted another staff member to come tell me "my colleague has previously told you that I have to tone down on the grunting and shouting" and "it's in the rules".
I pointed to the list of rules and asked which rule stated that I couldn't grunt or shout?
That guy didn't even know, he had to ask his other colleague which rule actually stated that.
He said it was under rowdy behaviour, his friends didn't even have a towel, which was under the rule: MUST HAVE A TOWEL.
So, at which point should rules be enforced, and other rules be more flexible?

Erol was the staff member which enforced the rule.
